[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] You can use the `Object()` constructor to create an object wrapper of a primitive value.
[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] When altering the behavior of existing `Object.prototype` methods, consider injecting code by wrapping your extension before or after the existing logic.
[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] For example, this (untested) code will pre-conditionally execute custom logic before the built-in logic or someone else's extension is executed.
[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] When modifying prototypes with hooks, pass `this` and the arguments (the call state) to the current behavior by calling `apply()` on the function.
[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] This pattern can be used for any prototype, such as `Node.prototype`, `Function.prototype`, etc.
[src:prisma-client/global-objects-object] You can read more about prototypes in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:prisma-client/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Prisma Client can be used in *any* Node.js or TypeScript backend application (including serverless applications and microservices).
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] This can be a REST API, a GraphQL API, a gRPC API, or anything else that needs a database.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] The fastest way to get started with Prisma is by following the quickstart guides.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] This section provides a high-level overview of how Prisma ORM works and its most important technical components.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] For a more thorough introduction, visit the Prisma documentation.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Every project that uses a tool from the Prisma toolkit starts with a Prisma schema file.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] The Prisma schema allows developers to define their *application models* in an intuitive data modeling language and configure *generators*.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Database connection details are defined via `prisma.config.ts`.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Prisma ORM does not load the `.env` files for you automatically.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If you want to populate the environment variables from a `.env` file, consider using a package such as `dotenv` or `@dotenvx/dotenvx`.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] On this page, the focus is on the data model.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] You can learn more about Data sources and Generators on the respective docs pages.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] The data model is a collection of models.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Once the data model is defined, you can generate Prisma Client which will expose CRUD and more queries for the defined models.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If you're using TypeScript, you'll get full type-safety for all queries (even when only retrieving the subsets of a model's fields).
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Configure the Prisma CLI using a `prisma.config.ts` file.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] This file configures Prisma CLI subcommands like `migrate` and `studio`.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Learn more about Prisma Config and all available configuration options.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] This command reads your Prisma schema and *generates* the Prisma Client code in the location specified by the `output` path in your generator configuration.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Refer to the documentation for more information about "generating the Prisma client".
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Once the Prisma Client is generated, you can import it in your code and send queries to your database.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] You can import and instantiate Prisma Client from the output path specified in your generator configuration.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] When instantiating the Client, you need to provide a driver adapter to its constructor.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] To load environment variables, you can use `dotenv` by importing `dotenv/config`, use `tsx --env-file=.env`, `node --env-file=.env`, or Bun (which loads `.env` automatically).
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Now you can start sending queries via the generated Prisma Client API, here are a few sample queries.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Note that all Prisma Client queries return *plain old JavaScript objects*.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Learn more about the available operations in the Prisma Client docs or watch this demo video (2 min).
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Note that when using TypeScript, the result of this query will be *statically typed* so that you can't accidentally access a property that doesn't exist (and any typos are caught at compile-time).
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Learn more about leveraging Prisma Client's generated types on the Advanced usage of generated types page in the docs.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Prisma has a large and supportive community of enthusiastic application developers.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] You can join us on Discord and here on GitHub.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Built something awesome with Prisma? 🌟 Show it off with these badges, perfect for your readme or website.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If you have a security issue to report, please contact us at security@prisma.io.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] You can ask questions and initiate discussions about Prisma-related topics in the `prisma` repository on GitHub.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If you see an error message or run into an issue, please make sure to create a bug report!
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] You can find best practices for creating bug reports (like including additional debugging output) in the docs.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If Prisma currently doesn't have a certain feature, be sure to check out the roadmap to see if this is already planned for the future.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] If the feature on the roadmap is linked to a GitHub issue, please make sure to leave a 👍 reaction on the issue and ideally a comment with your thoughts about the feature!
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Refer to our contribution guidelines and Code of Conduct for contributors.
[src:prisma-client/prisma-prisma] Scheduled CI is currently disabled across the ORM repos; test workflows run on push, pull request, and manual `workflow_dispatch`.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:prisma-client/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:prisma-client/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:prisma-client/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:prisma-client/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:prisma-client/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:prisma-client/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:prisma-client/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:prisma-client/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:prisma-client/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:prisma-client/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:prisma-client/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:prisma-client/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:prisma-client/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:prisma-client/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:prisma-client/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:prisma-client/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:prisma-client/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:prisma-client/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:prisma-client/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:prisma-client/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:prisma-client/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:prisma-client/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:prisma-client/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:prisma-client/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:prisma-client/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:prisma-client/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:prisma-client/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:prisma-client/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:prisma-client/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] This page gives a high-level overview of what Prisma ORM is and how it works.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] It's a great starting point for Prisma newcomers!
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Prisma ORM is an open-source next-generation ORM.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Prisma Client can be used in *any* Node.js (supported versions) or TypeScript backend application (including serverless applications and microservices).
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Every project that uses a tool from the Prisma ORM toolkit starts with a Prisma schema.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] The Prisma schema allows developers to define their *application models* in an intuitive data modeling language.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Database connection URLs are configured in a `prisma.config.ts` file.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] When using Prisma CLI commands, environment variables are not automatically loaded.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] You'll need to use a package like `dotenv` to load environment variables from a `.env` file, or ensure your environment variables are set in your shell.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] The `prisma generate` command reads your Prisma schema and *generates* Prisma Client code.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] The code is generated into the path specified in the `output` field of your generator block (e.g., `./generated` as shown in the schema example above).
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] After you change your data model, you'll need to manually re-generate Prisma Client by running `prisma generate` to ensure the generated code gets updated.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Once Prisma Client has been generated, you can import it in your code and send queries to your database.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Learn more about the available operations in the Prisma Client API reference.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] As mentioned above, there are two ways for "getting" your data model into the Prisma schema.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Depending on which approach you choose, your main Prisma ORM workflow might look different.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] If for some reason, you can not or do not want to use Prisma Migrate, you can still use introspection to update your Prisma schema from your database schema.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] To learn more about the introspection workflow, please refer the introspection section.
[src:prisma-client/what-is-prisma] Learn about the motivation for Prisma ORM and how it compares to other Node.js and TypeScript database tools like ORMs and SQL query builders.
